00:04:35.900 --> 00:04:38.340
So there's a lot going on there.

00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:41.540
But, essentially, you can
just think of the LEIF

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:44.810
that we've taken the
mechanics of snowboarding

00:04:44.810 --> 00:04:48.890
and traded the potential energy
that a mountain gives you,

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:54.350
mountain slope, and for the
electronic mechanical energy

00:04:54.350 --> 00:04:56.570
of electronic motors.

00:04:56.570 --> 00:04:59.780
And so really the key
secret sauce to our system

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:02.220
is this 360 drive
that you see here.

00:05:02.220 --> 00:05:04.751
So this is really
a caster wheel just

00:05:04.751 --> 00:05:07.250
like you see on the bottom of
the shopping cart with a motor

00:05:07.250 --> 00:05:12.020
strapped to it and transmitting
energy through a slip ring,

00:05:12.020 --> 00:05:15.740
and going into a battery pack,
and controlled by your hand.

00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:18.680
And so those drive
wheels, the base of it,

00:05:18.680 --> 00:05:20.490
are a little bit
lower to the ground.

00:05:20.490 --> 00:05:22.970
And you can see in the
tilting and drifting

00:05:22.970 --> 00:05:28.190
part the outer edge wheels, they
function just like a snowboard,

00:05:28.190 --> 00:05:29.650
so the edges on your snowboard.

00:05:29.650 --> 00:05:32.540
And that's really there for
just steering, and control,

00:05:32.540 --> 00:05:33.560
and braking.

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:35.240
And the rest is you.

00:05:35.240 --> 00:05:38.780
Your whole body controls
this crazy experience just

00:05:38.780 --> 00:05:40.070
like a snowboard.

00:05:40.070 --> 00:05:42.050
And it's really almost magical.

00:05:42.050 --> 00:05:45.080
If you know how to
snowboard, and you

00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:48.350
take all of those, that muscle
memory, and that experience,

00:05:48.350 --> 00:05:51.360
and you jump on the Leaf, and
you can channel that through,

00:05:51.360 --> 00:05:52.580
it just works.

00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:57.950
In fact, it only works if you
ride it just like a snowboard.

00:05:57.950 --> 00:05:58.460
So

00:05:58.460 --> 00:05:59.450
How do you stop?

00:05:59.450 --> 00:06:00.860
Very important question.

00:06:00.860 --> 00:06:04.640
You stop just like a snowboard,
so sliding on your edge wheels

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:07.430
just like you slide on
the edge of a snowboard.

00:06:07.430 --> 00:06:10.520
It's the most fun and most
effective way of stopping.

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:13.550
You can go from our top
speed of 23 miles an hour

00:06:13.550 --> 00:06:16.970
to a dead stop in less
than two car lengths, which

00:06:16.970 --> 00:06:18.857
if you try that on a
bike or something else,

00:06:18.857 --> 00:06:20.690
you might, you know,
go over the handlebars,

00:06:20.690 --> 00:06:22.610
but you're leaning into that--

00:06:22.610 --> 00:06:24.330
that slide and that force.

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:28.170
So you can stop really hard
and be really comfortable.

00:06:28.170 --> 00:06:32.040
So it gives you a lot of control
when you're at top speed.

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:35.220
And you might have noticed there
is these hooks that kind of fit

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:36.390
over your feet.

00:06:36.390 --> 00:06:40.860
And this adds a ton of
control, just like a snowboard.

00:06:40.860 --> 00:06:44.730
Now with a snowboard, you're
locked on, and so you can't--

00:06:44.730 --> 00:06:47.460
there's no safety bailout
for the snowboard.

00:06:47.460 --> 00:06:49.300
But you have snow
under you, so it's OK.

00:06:49.300 --> 00:06:51.570
But when you're
operating over pavement,

00:06:51.570 --> 00:06:55.260
you definitely want to have
the ability to jump off,

00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:56.801
and it's funny,
once you-- once you

00:06:56.801 --> 00:06:58.300
get rolling on the
LEIF for a while,

00:06:58.300 --> 00:07:00.870
and you go back to
snowboarding, you're

00:07:00.870 --> 00:07:04.382
kind of weirdly freaked out by
the ability you can't jump off.

00:07:04.382 --> 00:07:06.840
So it kind of takes a couple
of rounds to get back into it.

00:07:06.840 --> 00:07:09.720
But that's a key
feature and a must

00:07:09.720 --> 00:07:13.280
for getting out these footholds.

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:16.850
And so on the acceleration,
it's a wireless remote control.

00:07:16.850 --> 00:07:19.670
And so you can think of
this as kind of controlling

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:21.200
your mountain slope.

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:23.390
And so if you have it
all the way forward,

00:07:23.390 --> 00:07:25.190
the gas pedal completely
hammered down,

00:07:25.190 --> 00:07:28.400
that's like a triple black
diamond, like, dropping in,

00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:30.770
just getting off super fast.

00:07:30.770 --> 00:07:34.280
Or you can just really lightly
move the controller forward,

00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:37.010
and it can be like a
nice bunny hill slope.

00:07:37.010 --> 00:07:39.170
But the nice thing is, is
that at any point in time

00:07:39.170 --> 00:07:42.380
if you get nervous, if you get
a little bit out of control,

00:07:42.380 --> 00:07:45.760
you can let go, and the motors
will just coast and eventually

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:47.010
will come to a stop.

00:07:47.010 --> 00:07:49.070
And so, really, it's a
bit like snowboarding,

00:07:49.070 --> 00:07:52.650
but you can make the mountain
go away any time you want.

00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:55.940
And then we made the battery
swappable, because if you're

00:07:55.940 --> 00:07:57.740
a snowboarder, even
if you've never

00:07:57.740 --> 00:08:01.040
dreamed about snowboarding
on city streets,

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:03.279
you've definitely dreamed
about the endless slope

00:08:03.279 --> 00:08:05.820
because at some point, you get
to the bottom of the mountain,

00:08:05.820 --> 00:08:09.120
which is a total drag because
you have to wait in line,

00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:10.850
get in a lift up,
and so you always

00:08:10.850 --> 00:08:12.710
dream about that endless slope.

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:13.930
And we wanted that ability.

00:08:13.930 --> 00:08:16.010
And so for us the
endless slope is

00:08:16.010 --> 00:08:18.170
getting to the end of
a battery, not having

00:08:18.170 --> 00:08:21.050
to go home and charge it,
but rather just switch out

00:08:21.050 --> 00:08:23.780
another battery and keep going.

00:08:23.780 --> 00:08:26.900
These batteries will go up to
15 miles on our largest size,

00:08:26.900 --> 00:08:28.610
and so far, I
haven't seen anybody

00:08:28.610 --> 00:08:29.870
go past three batteries.

00:08:29.870 --> 00:08:33.909
That's been kind of the human
limit of fun at this point.

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:42.260
Yeah, so before I get into
this part, this project,

00:08:42.260 --> 00:08:46.030
I mean, from the beginning,
I mean, the crux of this

00:08:46.030 --> 00:08:47.770
was figuring out that
powered cast reel.

00:08:47.770 --> 00:08:50.990
That was the thing that
electronic engineers,

00:08:50.990 --> 00:08:54.400
mechanical engineers, investors,
friends and family all told

00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:57.230
us was probably impossible.

00:08:57.230 --> 00:08:59.390
But none of us are engineers.

00:08:59.390 --> 00:09:02.350
So we didn't have that
experience to kind of think

00:09:02.350 --> 00:09:03.110
it was impossible.

00:09:03.110 --> 00:09:05.000
We just knew this had to happen.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.530
We just knew that if we could
bring this experience to 365

00:09:08.530 --> 00:09:13.360
days a year, the
idea is just so big

00:09:13.360 --> 00:09:16.160
and such a big life
improvement for snowboarders.

00:09:16.160 --> 00:09:17.040
And so we just--

00:09:17.040 --> 00:09:19.820
we-- they didn't understand
we had to make it happen.

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:24.220
And so we had to kind of go the
bootstrapping route, especially

00:09:24.220 --> 00:09:28.522
since we didn't have
a lot of funding.

00:09:28.522 --> 00:09:30.730
And, again, you know, when
we were pitching investors

00:09:30.730 --> 00:09:32.938
in the beginning trying to
convince them to snowboard

00:09:32.938 --> 00:09:35.110
everywhere, they just--

00:09:35.110 --> 00:09:36.042
nobody would believe.

00:09:36.042 --> 00:09:37.750
Even Kickstarter didn't
believe, in fact.

00:09:37.750 --> 00:09:40.270
When we launched
our Kickstarter,

00:09:40.270 --> 00:09:43.660
they flagged us for spam because
they thought it was fake.

00:09:43.660 --> 00:09:47.845
And, luckily, I-- I was--
we built this in Brooklyn.

00:09:47.845 --> 00:09:48.970
Kickstarter is in Brooklyn.

00:09:48.970 --> 00:09:51.460
So when I got that email,
I was pretty annoyed

00:09:51.460 --> 00:09:52.590
because it was real.

00:09:52.590 --> 00:09:54.850
And so we just
grabbed the board,

00:09:54.850 --> 00:09:56.530
rode over to Kickstarter's
headquarters,

00:09:56.530 --> 00:09:58.696
and just did laps in their
lobby until they launched

00:09:58.696 --> 00:10:00.930
our campaign, which
only took about an hour,

00:10:00.930 --> 00:10:03.460
but he got up and
were up and running.

00:10:03.460 --> 00:10:06.370
But there were a number of
lessons that we learned along

00:10:06.370 --> 00:10:08.390
the way because when
we-- we started this,

00:10:08.390 --> 00:10:11.200
it was kind of early, and a lot
of harder projects happening

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:12.000
now, but--

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.770
but a few years ago, it
was kind of desperate,

00:10:14.770 --> 00:10:19.420
and there wasn't like a tutorial
out there, even a roadmap,

00:10:19.420 --> 00:10:21.670
on how to bootstrap hardware.

00:10:21.670 --> 00:10:23.500
But we learned-- we
were able to do it,

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:25.291
and we learned a lot
of lessons on the way,

00:10:25.291 --> 00:10:26.780
so I'll share those with you.

00:10:26.780 --> 00:10:30.410
Number one, YouTube
is the Matrix.

00:10:30.410 --> 00:10:34.450
And what I mean by that is my
favorite part of "The Matrix"

00:10:34.450 --> 00:10:37.120
wasn't like dodging
bullets or flying.

00:10:37.120 --> 00:10:41.251
It was like downloading skills
to your brain instantly.

00:10:41.251 --> 00:10:43.000
That was what I was
most fascinated about.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:44.800
If I could take anything
from "The Matrix"

00:10:44.800 --> 00:10:46.841
and put it in real life,
that's why I would pick.

00:10:46.841 --> 00:10:49.210
And that's what
YouTube is in a way.

00:10:49.210 --> 00:10:51.170
I mean, I'm not an engineer.

00:10:51.170 --> 00:10:54.220
I knew nothing about what we--

00:10:54.220 --> 00:10:57.490
all this technology that we had
to put together for this board,

00:10:57.490 --> 00:11:02.980
and I remember it was like one
lazy Thanksgiving afternoon.

00:11:02.980 --> 00:11:03.820
Everybody had eaten.

00:11:03.820 --> 00:11:05.579
We were just kind of
all laying around.

00:11:05.579 --> 00:11:07.120
And I thought, wow,
I'd really rather

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:09.560
be snowboarding right now.

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:11.570
And I had an electric
skateboard at the time.

00:11:11.570 --> 00:11:13.278
And I was thinking,
like, this would just

00:11:13.278 --> 00:11:16.570
be such a better experience
if it felt like snowboarding.

00:11:16.570 --> 00:11:18.370
It would be game changing.

00:11:18.370 --> 00:11:21.370
And so I started kind of
thinking about those pieces

00:11:21.370 --> 00:11:23.100
of my electric skateboard.

00:11:23.100 --> 00:11:25.750
And I started searching,
OK, lithium ion batteries

00:11:25.750 --> 00:11:26.530
was a big feature.

00:11:26.530 --> 00:11:27.730
I knew nothing.

00:11:27.730 --> 00:11:29.650
What is a lithium ion battery?

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:32.550
And I found on YouTube a
lecture from Carnegie Mellon,

00:11:32.550 --> 00:11:36.260
90 minutes, about lithium
ion battery technology.

00:11:36.260 --> 00:11:38.470
And that was four years ago.

00:11:38.470 --> 00:11:40.840
We've actually gone through
a lot, built this product.

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:44.200
I know maybe 5% more than I
did that day after watching

00:11:44.200 --> 00:11:47.170
that lecture, and, you
know, I watched it,

00:11:47.170 --> 00:11:49.630
and as like, kind of like, you
know, unplugged the Matrix,

00:11:49.630 --> 00:11:53.110
and I was like, I know
lithium ion batteries.

00:11:53.110 --> 00:11:54.820
And then I was
like, OK, how do I--

00:11:54.820 --> 00:11:56.660
how do I go to the next piece?

00:11:56.660 --> 00:12:00.282
How do you put electricity
through a rotating circuit?

00:12:00.282 --> 00:12:02.740
And turns out there's these
things called slip rings that I

00:12:02.740 --> 00:12:04.198
didn't even know
about, and they're

00:12:04.198 --> 00:12:06.820
in everything, a headphone
jack, in fact, is a slip ring.

00:12:06.820 --> 00:12:08.720
And so I saw a few
videos on those.

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:12.050
And we kind of had to reinvent
the slip ring a little bit,

00:12:12.050 --> 00:12:13.810
but the main idea was there.

00:12:13.810 --> 00:12:14.840
I knew, OK, we've--

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:16.090
there's got to be a slip ring.

00:12:16.090 --> 00:12:18.040
There's got to be
electronic batteries.

00:12:18.040 --> 00:12:20.425
There's got to be motors and--

00:12:20.425 --> 00:12:22.630
you know, in a lazy afternoon,
you can surprisingly

00:12:22.630 --> 00:12:25.064
get a lot done on
YouTube if you spin

00:12:25.064 --> 00:12:26.230
it the right way, of course.

00:12:26.230 --> 00:12:30.970
But my biggest, I guess,
advice to even engineers

00:12:30.970 --> 00:12:34.090
is, if you don't know
anything about the technology,

00:12:34.090 --> 00:12:36.970
there's probably a
YouTube video out there.

00:12:36.970 --> 00:12:38.470
And, you know, even
if it's some guy

00:12:38.470 --> 00:12:39.850
in his garage
putting a tutorial,

00:12:39.850 --> 00:12:41.266
sometimes those
are the best ones.

00:12:44.170 --> 00:12:47.700
Next we-- kind of came up
with a way of doing PR,

00:12:47.700 --> 00:12:50.090
and we called it
downstairs demo.

00:12:50.090 --> 00:12:53.080
And so traditionally
with PR, it's

00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:55.090
a big part of
bootstrapping something

00:12:55.090 --> 00:12:56.890
because you don't
have an ad budget,

00:12:56.890 --> 00:12:59.042
and you probably can't
even hire a PR agent.

00:12:59.042 --> 00:13:00.500
And so you've got
to get, you know,

00:13:00.500 --> 00:13:03.760
organic articles out there
that you aren't paying for.

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:06.190
And, traditionally,
you know, you--

00:13:06.190 --> 00:13:08.954
you research the writers
that you think you can--

00:13:08.954 --> 00:13:10.870
that would be interested
in what you're doing.

00:13:10.870 --> 00:13:13.930
You look at their interests,
the topics that they like,

00:13:13.930 --> 00:13:15.996
and how you can
position your company.

00:13:15.996 --> 00:13:17.620
And you write an
awesome email that you

00:13:17.620 --> 00:13:19.960
send at 10:00 AM on Tuesday
to kind of catch them

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:21.250
in between tasks.

00:13:21.250 --> 00:13:23.740
But the problem is, everybody's
doing that, you know?

00:13:23.740 --> 00:13:26.770
They're getting thousands of
emails at 10 AM on Tuesday.

00:13:26.770 --> 00:13:30.400
And, unfortunately, most
likely, it won't get read.

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:33.610
And so you have to take
it a step further in what

00:13:33.610 --> 00:13:35.320
we call the downstairs demo.

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:37.900
And the first step
to that is find out

00:13:37.900 --> 00:13:40.319
where they work, the
address to where they work.

00:13:40.319 --> 00:13:41.860
This is getting
creepy, but just hang

00:13:41.860 --> 00:13:43.220
in there with me for a second.

00:13:43.220 --> 00:13:47.830
So you find out where they work,
and you show up maybe an hour

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:51.790
before or after lunch, maybe
the last hour of the day,

00:13:51.790 --> 00:13:53.041
and you get up to their lobby.

00:13:53.041 --> 00:13:55.373
You're not going to get past
the lobby, but don't worry,

00:13:55.373 --> 00:13:57.040
you don't have to
get past the lobby.

00:13:57.040 --> 00:14:00.250
You just take your
smartphone, and you

00:14:00.250 --> 00:14:03.805
film yourself using your
device in their lobby

00:14:03.805 --> 00:14:06.430
or in front of their building if
they kick you out of the lobby

00:14:06.430 --> 00:14:08.230
or on the street if
they make you get off

00:14:08.230 --> 00:14:10.607
the foyer, which has happened.

00:14:10.607 --> 00:14:12.940
And in our case, you know,
just doing donuts and saying,

00:14:12.940 --> 00:14:15.190
hey, look, you're one
short elevator ride

00:14:15.190 --> 00:14:18.540
away from trying
this crazy new tech.

00:14:18.540 --> 00:14:21.420
That got a 100% response rate.

00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:24.600
Not everybody came down, but
half the people came down,

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:26.100
and all those people
wrote about it.

00:14:26.100 --> 00:14:27.810
So that's how we
got in "The Verge,"

00:14:27.810 --> 00:14:31.890
"Engadget," "Gizmodo," and
a lot of big publications.

00:14:31.890 --> 00:14:34.020
The other half of
the people all said

00:14:34.020 --> 00:14:35.860
the exact same
thing, which is, hey,

00:14:35.860 --> 00:14:40.230
I've been burned by hardware
startup Kickstarter projects

00:14:40.230 --> 00:14:40.760
before.

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:42.450
And I just can't
write about you.

00:14:42.450 --> 00:14:43.980
If you can figure that
out before you show up

00:14:43.980 --> 00:14:45.480
to their lobby,
that would be great.

00:14:45.480 --> 00:14:48.000
But, you know, sometimes
you just have to show up.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:49.360
But that's a big thing.

00:14:49.360 --> 00:14:51.150
I mean, we were lucky
we were in New York.

00:14:51.150 --> 00:14:53.070
And it was convenient,
but when we did this,

00:14:53.070 --> 00:14:55.260
we did it in one to two days.

00:14:55.260 --> 00:14:58.500
And so quick trip to New
York, or LA, or wherever,

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:02.390
if you're not in these areas,
you can get a lot done.

00:15:02.390 --> 00:15:05.280
OK, so on the
prototyping side, you're

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:08.070
going to need a 3D printer if
you're prototyping hardware

00:15:08.070 --> 00:15:10.800
because rapid
prototyping is just--

00:15:10.800 --> 00:15:12.780
it's not rapid.

00:15:12.780 --> 00:15:14.609
You know, you're talking
one to-- you know,

00:15:14.609 --> 00:15:16.650
one to three days on the
fastest turnaround time,

00:15:16.650 --> 00:15:18.310
and it's incredibly expensive.

00:15:18.310 --> 00:15:20.340
In fact, on the first,
you know, two models,

00:15:20.340 --> 00:15:22.080
you might send a
rapid prototyping,

00:15:22.080 --> 00:15:24.140
you could actually
buy a 3D printer.

00:15:24.140 --> 00:15:26.310
And once you make
that $1,000 to $3,000

00:15:26.310 --> 00:15:29.700
investment for a 3D
printer, it's almost free,

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:33.540
and you can obviously
iterate your prototypes

00:15:33.540 --> 00:15:35.190
a lot faster by
printing them at home

00:15:35.190 --> 00:15:36.990
because you are--
you have become

00:15:36.990 --> 00:15:39.330
essentially a rapid prototyper.

00:15:39.330 --> 00:15:42.940
But there's ways to even
speed it up beyond that.

00:15:42.940 --> 00:15:46.200
So, for example, say you've
got a small motor mount

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:48.450
that's part of your
project, and you've

00:15:48.450 --> 00:15:50.580
got eight features
that, you know,

00:15:50.580 --> 00:15:53.910
holes, or things that
fit into other things

00:15:53.910 --> 00:15:55.140
as part of your project.

00:15:55.140 --> 00:15:57.189
And you have to dial
in each one at a time.

00:15:57.189 --> 00:15:58.980
Now, say this a little
motor mount out only

00:15:58.980 --> 00:16:03.330
takes an hour to print, which
is a pretty fast print, OK?

00:16:03.330 --> 00:16:05.820
You've got eight features,
each one, we'll say,

00:16:05.820 --> 00:16:08.650
takes two or three, kind
of prints to get it right.

00:16:08.650 --> 00:16:10.740
That's 20 prints you
have to make to dial in

00:16:10.740 --> 00:16:12.610
that one motor mount.

00:16:12.610 --> 00:16:15.570
Now, that's still light speed
compared to rapid prototyping.

00:16:15.570 --> 00:16:19.410
You won't even get an email back
from the company in 20 hours.

00:16:19.410 --> 00:16:21.150
But you can go way faster.

00:16:21.150 --> 00:16:25.380
And that is by printing
in 2D rather than 3D.

00:16:25.380 --> 00:16:28.020
And so if you've got that
that motor mount, and you're

00:16:28.020 --> 00:16:30.120
trying to dial in a
hole, you can actually

00:16:30.120 --> 00:16:34.920
just print a 1 millimeter
layer face and, you know,

00:16:34.920 --> 00:16:38.130
peel it off, get your calipers
out, measure it, dial it in.

00:16:38.130 --> 00:16:39.660
And you can print
that 1 millimeter

00:16:39.660 --> 00:16:41.820
layer in two minutes.

00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:44.010
So 20 prints
instead of 20 hours,

00:16:44.010 --> 00:16:46.410
you just turn it into
40 minutes of printing.

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:50.157
And that's how you can dial in
entire parts of an afternoon.

00:16:50.157 --> 00:16:51.615
And that was a big,
big lesson kind

00:16:51.615 --> 00:16:53.620
of we learned along
that way, and, you know,

00:16:53.620 --> 00:16:56.540
it took literally days to kind
of get all this stuff together

00:16:56.540 --> 00:16:58.320
and be on the road.

00:17:01.330 --> 00:17:03.430
Definitely iterate with
off-the-shelf components,

00:17:03.430 --> 00:17:05.650
and this isn't
anything, a new idea,

00:17:05.650 --> 00:17:09.130
but you definitely have to
kind of think about some

00:17:09.130 --> 00:17:11.170
of the constraints
that might come

00:17:11.170 --> 00:17:12.910
with those off-the-shelf
components.

00:17:12.910 --> 00:17:15.050
And we had to deal
with one in particular

00:17:15.050 --> 00:17:16.780
that was a little scary.

00:17:16.780 --> 00:17:20.349
So our first version
of this, we basically

00:17:20.349 --> 00:17:22.839
took apart an
electronic helicopter,

00:17:22.839 --> 00:17:25.270
put the motors on a
shopping cart wheel,

00:17:25.270 --> 00:17:27.430
and put that onto a skateboard.

00:17:27.430 --> 00:17:29.540
And we were off and running.

00:17:29.540 --> 00:17:32.330
And what we didn't
realize, though,

00:17:32.330 --> 00:17:34.510
is a feature of electronic
helicopters, which

00:17:34.510 --> 00:17:37.210
is great when you're flying.

00:17:37.210 --> 00:17:40.390
If you lose radio signal,
it'll go full speed

00:17:40.390 --> 00:17:43.570
to stay in the air.

00:17:43.570 --> 00:17:46.900
I think you guys understand
where I'm going with this.

00:17:46.900 --> 00:17:49.520
We'd be riding around,
and in New York City,

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:54.520
maybe the most dense place
of 2.5 gigahertz networks,

00:17:54.520 --> 00:17:57.550
and when you lose
signal, you go full speed

00:17:57.550 --> 00:17:59.050
for a good like
one to two seconds

00:17:59.050 --> 00:18:00.440
until it kind of gets back.

00:18:00.440 --> 00:18:02.470
So it was kind of
this mechanical bull

00:18:02.470 --> 00:18:05.500
that you had to be just ready
to go full speed at any given

00:18:05.500 --> 00:18:06.770
time.

00:18:06.770 --> 00:18:09.470
And so we kind of learned with
these parts, OK, you know,

00:18:09.470 --> 00:18:10.730
we learned these constraints.

00:18:10.730 --> 00:18:12.310
And so a lot
off-the-shelf parts,

00:18:12.310 --> 00:18:14.890
you kind of have to read a
lot more of the directions

00:18:14.890 --> 00:18:17.610
than you might be prepared
to before you get going.

00:18:20.270 --> 00:18:24.180
Then the mobile lab, so you
definitely with hardware,

00:18:24.180 --> 00:18:26.180
you're going to be doing
a lot of field testing.

00:18:26.180 --> 00:18:27.980
And in the beginning,
you're going

00:18:27.980 --> 00:18:31.790
to be doing a lot more
fixing than actually testing

00:18:31.790 --> 00:18:35.362
in the field, and those
minutes that turn into hours,

00:18:35.362 --> 00:18:37.070
and eventually turn
into days of testing,

00:18:37.070 --> 00:18:39.195
they're like gold
in the beginning,

00:18:39.195 --> 00:18:41.570
and, you know, when you're
out in the field and something

00:18:41.570 --> 00:18:44.210
breaks, which in the beginning,
will happen in the first two

00:18:44.210 --> 00:18:46.265
minutes, you know,
you don't want

00:18:46.265 --> 00:18:47.649
to have to go back
to the office,

00:18:47.649 --> 00:18:49.940
you know, 45-minute train
ride, and go fix it, and then

00:18:49.940 --> 00:18:51.890
go back out to the field.

00:18:51.890 --> 00:18:53.810
You need to take your
mobile lab with you.

00:18:53.810 --> 00:18:56.540
And so, obviously, there's
like a lot of mechanical things

00:18:56.540 --> 00:19:01.190
that are built for going with
you like electronic drills,

00:19:01.190 --> 00:19:03.390
wrenches, things like that.

00:19:03.390 --> 00:19:05.940
But eventually, you know,
you're going to have to solder,

00:19:05.940 --> 00:19:08.180
and soldering
irons unfortunately

00:19:08.180 --> 00:19:11.630
take a lot of current because
they have to get really hot,

00:19:11.630 --> 00:19:13.410
and you won't always
have a plug with you,

00:19:13.410 --> 00:19:17.150
especially if you're, you know,
going on New York City testing

00:19:17.150 --> 00:19:18.300
your product.

00:19:18.300 --> 00:19:20.960
So you have to find plugs
around, but they exist.

00:19:20.960 --> 00:19:24.740
You know, we've soldered
outside a public bathroom

00:19:24.740 --> 00:19:26.750
in Central Park.

00:19:26.750 --> 00:19:29.330
I've soldered in a coat
closet at the Plaza Hotel.

00:19:29.330 --> 00:19:32.360
They're nice enough to let
me get in there and solder.

00:19:32.360 --> 00:19:34.880
They have these random plugs
in the ceilings in the subway

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:36.689
that you can-- you
can dial into and get

00:19:36.689 --> 00:19:37.730
enough current to solder.

00:19:37.730 --> 00:19:40.460
But just bring the whole
lab with you, like,

00:19:40.460 --> 00:19:42.725
don't think you have to go
back and just, you know,

00:19:42.725 --> 00:19:43.850
carry everything around.

00:19:43.850 --> 00:19:45.475
If you've got to drag
a wagon with you,

00:19:45.475 --> 00:19:47.370
it's really worth it
because, again, it's

00:19:47.370 --> 00:19:49.670
going to be two
minutes of testing

00:19:49.670 --> 00:19:53.780
and two hours of fixing
in the beginning.

00:19:53.780 --> 00:19:58.090
And, so, you know, I could go on
and on about hardware stories,

00:19:58.090 --> 00:19:58.690
startups.

00:19:58.690 --> 00:20:01.450
But I think maybe this is a
good time to just switch it over

00:20:01.450 --> 00:20:04.840
