So Chris actually did that.

00:23:44.734 --> 00:23:46.150
And I told him, I
said, OK, you're

00:23:46.150 --> 00:23:50.560
going to have to catch a
front edge and bail out,

00:23:50.560 --> 00:23:53.380
which if you do this on
a snowboard, there's no--

00:23:53.380 --> 00:23:55.100
there's no turning back.

00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:57.020
I mean, you're going
to go face down.

00:23:57.020 --> 00:24:00.340
So we probably should
have this in slow mo.

00:24:00.340 --> 00:24:03.100
But more or less,
when you're to get out

00:24:03.100 --> 00:24:06.000
and eject really easily, you--

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.810
the footholds are kind
of out from the edge.

00:24:08.810 --> 00:24:12.340
So when you're riding, you're
putting outward pressure

00:24:12.340 --> 00:24:15.700
with your feet to really, like,
hold in and kind of maintain

00:24:15.700 --> 00:24:17.170
that position.

00:24:17.170 --> 00:24:20.200
But to get out, you just
bring your feet together.

00:24:20.200 --> 00:24:21.700
And if you bring
your feet together,

00:24:21.700 --> 00:24:23.240
you can even jump forward.

00:24:23.240 --> 00:24:26.320
But if you don't, you know, you
can jump backwards or whatever.

00:24:26.320 --> 00:24:28.236
But, yeah, we're
kind of trained,

00:24:28.236 --> 00:24:29.860
and you get a muscle
memory after doing

00:24:29.860 --> 00:24:31.450
it a couple of times
and just, like,

00:24:31.450 --> 00:24:33.430
hopping together
and getting out.

00:24:33.430 --> 00:24:36.220
And you can adjust the
height, and how tight it

00:24:36.220 --> 00:24:37.540
is, and things like that.

00:24:37.540 --> 00:24:39.700
So you-- I ride a
little bit looser

00:24:39.700 --> 00:24:43.837
because I like to be able
to jump out very easily.

00:24:43.837 --> 00:24:44.920
But you want that control.

00:24:44.920 --> 00:24:46.960
You want to be
able to really like

00:24:46.960 --> 00:24:48.490
press in because
that's really going

00:24:48.490 --> 00:24:52.240
to give you that broad control.

00:24:52.240 --> 00:24:57.040
On the remote control, so there
is a trigger and a thumb wheel.

00:24:57.040 --> 00:24:59.050
And that's really--
you can find that

00:24:59.050 --> 00:25:02.650
on most wireless, remote
electronic ridables

00:25:02.650 --> 00:25:06.640
because there's the safety
or dead man switch, which

00:25:06.640 --> 00:25:07.815
in our case, is the trigger.

00:25:07.815 --> 00:25:09.190
And then there's
the thumb wheel,

00:25:09.190 --> 00:25:10.810
which is the accelerator.

00:25:10.810 --> 00:25:13.030
And there's kind of
two schools of thought,

00:25:13.030 --> 00:25:15.090
and the skateboarding,
or electric skateboarding

00:25:15.090 --> 00:25:16.460
community, is kind of
split down the middle.

00:25:16.460 --> 00:25:18.501
And it's just whether you
have the deadman switch

00:25:18.501 --> 00:25:20.590
on your thumb or
your forefinger,

00:25:20.590 --> 00:25:24.160
and you have the accelerator on
your thumb or the forefinger.

00:25:24.160 --> 00:25:27.132
So the other way of doing it
is putting the deadman's switch

00:25:27.132 --> 00:25:29.590
on your thumb, and then the
trigger kind of like, you know,

00:25:29.590 --> 00:25:31.365
the old little RC cars.

00:25:31.365 --> 00:25:33.490
The reason we didn't go
that route is because we do

00:25:33.490 --> 00:25:38.080
find that some people, when
they crash, they grip, you know?

00:25:38.080 --> 00:25:40.450
And you definitely don't
want to go full speed.

00:25:40.450 --> 00:25:44.454
And so, even in our
case, if you grip,

00:25:44.454 --> 00:25:46.870
you're not going to, you know,
likely move the thumb wheel

00:25:46.870 --> 00:25:47.930
forward.

00:25:47.930 --> 00:25:49.900
But moving the
thumb wheel backward

00:25:49.900 --> 00:25:54.130
will actually provide electronic
braking, which, typically, we

00:25:54.130 --> 00:25:56.260
only use if you're in
like a tight space,

00:25:56.260 --> 00:25:59.230
and you can't turn
sideways to brake.

00:25:59.230 --> 00:26:01.940
But the sliding
the brake, I mean,

00:26:01.940 --> 00:26:04.540
that's the most fun,
the most effective,

00:26:04.540 --> 00:26:08.170
and it actually got us
about less than half

00:26:08.170 --> 00:26:11.530
the product insurance rate as
a normal electric skateboard

00:26:11.530 --> 00:26:15.340
because with those brakes,
they're all electronic.

00:26:15.340 --> 00:26:17.170
And, you know, you
can lose your brakes

00:26:17.170 --> 00:26:21.970
by losing the wireless
signal, breaking a belt,

00:26:21.970 --> 00:26:25.030
or going over 25 miles
an hour, at which there's

00:26:25.030 --> 00:26:27.670
too much momentum to stop you.

00:26:27.670 --> 00:26:30.881
And so that provides a lot
of stability and safety.

