00:32:49.705 --> 00:32:51.330
AUDIENCE: Has anyone
ever done anything

00:32:51.330 --> 00:32:53.538
that you weren't expecting
them to do with the board?

00:32:56.331 --> 00:32:58.080
AARON ADERS: Well, I
think that, you know,

00:32:58.080 --> 00:33:01.440
the hardest part of this
project wasn't getting

00:33:01.440 --> 00:33:02.710
the thing invented, actually.

00:33:02.710 --> 00:33:06.930
We did that in about five
months from just an empty desk

00:33:06.930 --> 00:33:08.790
with drawings to,
actually, a thing

00:33:08.790 --> 00:33:11.400
on the ground that, you know,
you could slide stuff down.

00:33:11.400 --> 00:33:13.110
The hard part was
getting it to something

00:33:13.110 --> 00:33:17.370
that a consumer is not going to
break in the first 10 minutes.

00:33:17.370 --> 00:33:19.740
Yeah, I mean, I
think consumers will

00:33:19.740 --> 00:33:21.830
do like things with
your product that you

00:33:21.830 --> 00:33:26.980
wouldn't imagine, you know,
sitting on the motherboard,

00:33:26.980 --> 00:33:28.950
for example.

00:33:28.950 --> 00:33:32.670
But I think some of the
more surprising thing

00:33:32.670 --> 00:33:35.370
was just kind of how
quickly a lot of people

00:33:35.370 --> 00:33:36.433
have picked it up.

00:33:36.433 --> 00:33:38.119
You know, I think,
in my case, it

00:33:38.119 --> 00:33:40.410
was a little different because
I was riding prototypes.

00:33:40.410 --> 00:33:41.310
I would brake constantly.

00:33:41.310 --> 00:33:43.020
So it kind of took
me forever to learn.

00:33:43.020 --> 00:33:45.870
But seeing how quickly
people jump on and just start

00:33:45.870 --> 00:33:48.710
sliding around, I mean, just
blows my mind sometimes.

00:33:48.710 --> 00:33:51.880
I'm like, wow it took me
hours to get to that point.

00:33:51.880 --> 00:33:53.970
And they literally just
kind of jumped off.

00:33:53.970 --> 00:33:59.560
But the key thing was dialing
in the snowboard feel.

00:33:59.560 --> 00:34:01.860
And so if you
snowboard, we actually

00:34:01.860 --> 00:34:04.770
have you close your eyes
when we put you on the board

00:34:04.770 --> 00:34:07.650
for the first time, and
we control the speed,

00:34:07.650 --> 00:34:09.900
and you know, we let you--
we hold the shoulder so you

00:34:09.900 --> 00:34:11.191
have a little bit of stability.

00:34:11.191 --> 00:34:14.790
But if you close your eyes, and
you imagine you're on the snow,

00:34:14.790 --> 00:34:18.690
it just happens
immediately, just magically.

00:34:18.690 --> 00:34:20.500
But then when you open
your eyes, and you--

00:34:20.500 --> 00:34:22.874
you know, you see the pavement
and all these other things

00:34:22.874 --> 00:34:25.500
that kind of make you
nervous, then, you know, you--

00:34:25.500 --> 00:34:27.850
you've got to kind of
learn to get over that.

00:34:27.850 --> 00:34:30.389
But what we learned from
doing a lot of demos

00:34:30.389 --> 00:34:32.872
is, if someone has snowboarding
experience, just blindfold

00:34:32.872 --> 00:34:34.830
them, make them close
their eyes, do something,

00:34:34.830 --> 00:34:37.860
because then they'll feel
that in the first 10 seconds.

00:34:37.860 --> 00:34:40.254
And once they feel that slide--

00:34:40.254 --> 00:34:42.420
because it really does feel
like snow because you're

00:34:42.420 --> 00:34:43.800
kind of going
sideways, and like,

00:34:43.800 --> 00:34:46.080
that just doesn't
happen anywhere else,

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:47.270
then they're hooked.

00:34:47.270 --> 00:34:50.400
Then they will go through
and fall or do anything

00:34:50.400 --> 00:34:52.870
to kind of have
that feeling again.

00:34:52.870 --> 00:34:56.100
And so that was a big thing
we learned going on is,

00:34:56.100 --> 00:34:59.710
like, get a user sliding
as quickly as possible.

00:35:04.877 --> 00:35:07.460
AUDIENCE: So you're saying that
it's pretty easy to learn if I

00:35:07.460 --> 00:35:09.585
don't-- know how to snowboard,
but I don't know how

00:35:09.585 --> 00:35:11.000
to skateboard?

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:13.730
AARON ADERS: You're
actually better off.

00:35:13.730 --> 00:35:18.140
In fact, the best candidate that
we could ask for that has never

00:35:18.140 --> 00:35:20.030
got on a board
before is somebody

00:35:20.030 --> 00:35:22.130
that has never skateboarded
because there's

00:35:22.130 --> 00:35:24.380
certain things you have to
unlearn from skateboarding.

00:35:24.380 --> 00:35:26.671
If you ride this like a
skateboard, it just won't work.

00:35:26.671 --> 00:35:28.880
You'll be super
frustrated, somebody

00:35:28.880 --> 00:35:32.030
with snowboarding experience,
obviously, but also a surfer.

00:35:32.030 --> 00:35:34.430
So if you can surf
and snowboard,

00:35:34.430 --> 00:35:36.980
you'll pick it up pretty
quickly because surfing, I mean,

00:35:36.980 --> 00:35:40.580
you learn that middle balance
point because, you know,

00:35:40.580 --> 00:35:43.000
learning to surf, it feels
like you're-- you're on ice.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:43.850
It's just crazy.

00:35:43.850 --> 00:35:45.740
But you really learn to
kind of balance over.

00:35:45.740 --> 00:35:47.570
And that's a key
thing in the beginning

00:35:47.570 --> 00:35:49.319
because when we start
people on the board,

00:35:49.319 --> 00:35:51.650
we don't put them under the
footholds in the beginning

00:35:51.650 --> 00:35:52.970
because, you know, they've
got to kind of learn

00:35:52.970 --> 00:35:54.080
how to bail off.

00:35:54.080 --> 00:35:57.320
And so without those footholds
to pull the board around,

00:35:57.320 --> 00:36:00.220
you really have to maintain
that center balance.

00:36:00.220 --> 00:36:03.470
And we find that surfers
do really well with that.

00:36:03.470 --> 00:36:06.260
So, like, people from Brazil
just jump on the board,

00:36:06.260 --> 00:36:08.390
and they're just like gone.

00:36:08.390 --> 00:36:10.370
They pick it up really quickly.

00:36:10.370 --> 00:36:12.110
AUDIENCE: How much
is this board?

00:36:12.110 --> 00:36:16.370
AARON ADERS: So the 10-mile
model starts at $1,549,

00:36:16.370 --> 00:36:18.830
and, hopefully, if you're
watching this video,

00:36:18.830 --> 00:36:20.649
in a few years, it's a lot less.

00:36:20.649 --> 00:36:22.190
AUDIENCE: OK, and
then last question,

00:36:22.190 --> 00:36:24.835
so I remember a while
ago I saw this--

00:36:24.835 --> 00:36:26.210
I don't know if
this-- maybe this

00:36:26.210 --> 00:36:28.312
is the same company, Freebord?

00:36:28.312 --> 00:36:29.020
AARON ADERS: Yes.

00:36:29.020 --> 00:36:30.519
AUDIENCE: Basically,
it looks like--

00:36:30.519 --> 00:36:32.990
kind of looks like this
just without the motor.

00:36:32.990 --> 00:36:35.027
AARON ADERS: Yeah,
so, really, I mean,

00:36:35.027 --> 00:36:37.110
we definitely invented a
few things along the way.

00:36:37.110 --> 00:36:40.970
But, I mean, at a high level,
we just took existing tech

00:36:40.970 --> 00:36:43.530
and just put it in, combined
it in different ways.

00:36:43.530 --> 00:36:47.030
So the Freebord
plus the Boosted,

00:36:47.030 --> 00:36:48.760
you can kind of think of--

00:36:48.760 --> 00:36:51.135
AUDIENCE: Yeah, because I
remember thinking like at that,

00:36:51.135 --> 00:36:53.820
like, oh, I wish it would
just go and flatten.

00:36:53.820 --> 00:36:54.440
So--

00:36:54.440 --> 00:36:57.450
AARON ADERS: Yeah, no, when I
saw that for the first time,

00:36:57.450 --> 00:36:59.690
it was like, I've never
had a religious experience,

00:36:59.690 --> 00:37:02.180
but when I saw that,
it was like, it just--

00:37:02.180 --> 00:37:03.527
it was incredible.

00:37:03.527 --> 00:37:05.360
But then I did some
research, and, well, you

00:37:05.360 --> 00:37:07.484
have to have a hill, and
I was living in Manhattan,

00:37:07.484 --> 00:37:08.680
and there's like no hills.

00:37:08.680 --> 00:37:11.030
I was even going to buy just
[INAUDIBLE] in a parking

00:37:11.030 --> 00:37:11.530
garage.

00:37:11.530 --> 00:37:13.220
But as a skateboarder,
I know you

00:37:13.220 --> 00:37:15.800
get kicked out of parking
garages, like, instantly.

00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:17.810
So I was kind of
back to square one,

00:37:17.810 --> 00:37:20.120
but, you know, Boosted came out.

00:37:20.120 --> 00:37:23.420
And they were the first to use
the AC motors, these really

00:37:23.420 --> 00:37:24.730
tiny motors.

00:37:24.730 --> 00:37:28.760
And I got one, and I was like,
OK, I think it's possible now.

00:37:28.760 --> 00:37:32.750
But, again, that-- you know,
strapping it to a caster wheel,

00:37:32.750 --> 00:37:35.120
no one thought that was
possible, absolutely

00:37:35.120 --> 00:37:35.930
zero, nobody.

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:47.250
AUDIENCE: So do you think people
can use this to like train

00:37:47.250 --> 00:37:49.110
for snowboarding?

00:37:49.110 --> 00:37:50.940
Like someone who
wants a snowboard

00:37:50.940 --> 00:37:54.220
but doesn't know
how to do it yet?

00:37:54.220 --> 00:37:57.450
AARON ADERS: Yeah,
so we definitely--

00:37:57.450 --> 00:38:00.230
we want to be the gateway
drug to snowboarding,

00:38:00.230 --> 00:38:03.210
you know, for people in
areas that don't have snow.

00:38:03.210 --> 00:38:06.084
And I love so
snowboarding so much.

00:38:06.084 --> 00:38:08.250
And I just respect the sport
so much that, you know,

00:38:08.250 --> 00:38:10.800
when we launched,
I felt inherently

00:38:10.800 --> 00:38:12.270
that this could
make people better.

00:38:12.270 --> 00:38:14.521
But I didn't want to
make that claim up front,

00:38:14.521 --> 00:38:16.770
saying this is going to make
you a better snowboarder.

00:38:16.770 --> 00:38:18.450
But that is the
feedback we're getting

00:38:18.450 --> 00:38:21.300
from our customers, especially
people that have only

00:38:21.300 --> 00:38:24.390
been a couple times, and
they're really new to the sport,

00:38:24.390 --> 00:38:28.440
and they get the LEIF, and,
you know, one of my favorites

00:38:28.440 --> 00:38:30.660
was a customer we
have in Singapore

00:38:30.660 --> 00:38:32.520
that he'd been on
a couple trips,

00:38:32.520 --> 00:38:35.017
was just obsessed with
the sport, got our board.

00:38:35.017 --> 00:38:36.600
He went he went on
a snowboarding trip

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:40.280
with some buddies,
meanwhile, bought our board,

00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:42.990
and he got back to Singapore,
rode his board for three weeks,

00:38:42.990 --> 00:38:46.410
went on another snowboarding
trip with the same buddies,

00:38:46.410 --> 00:38:49.230
and they all were, like,
you just had a whole season.

00:38:49.230 --> 00:38:49.995
What happened?

00:38:49.995 --> 00:38:51.660
Like, you got way better.

00:38:51.660 --> 00:38:53.225
And that's the thing.

00:38:53.225 --> 00:38:54.600
I mean, when you're
snowboarding,

00:38:54.600 --> 00:38:58.381
when you take into account lift
lines, and lifts, and lunch,

00:38:58.381 --> 00:38:59.880
and, you know, the
first day, you're

00:38:59.880 --> 00:39:02.160
going to be smoked in the
first couple of hours.

00:39:02.160 --> 00:39:05.040
You might only have of
like real actual riding,

00:39:05.040 --> 00:39:07.210
you know, just a
few hours a day.

00:39:07.210 --> 00:39:10.800
And so, you know, if you
can get out with the LEIF

00:39:10.800 --> 00:39:13.030
and one battery will
last you a few hours,

00:39:13.030 --> 00:39:15.238
and you can charge that a
couple times a day, I mean,

00:39:15.238 --> 00:39:18.900
you can get seasons of
riding in literally weeks.

00:39:18.900 --> 00:39:21.720
So, yeah, we were really happy
to see that it was actually

00:39:21.720 --> 00:39:24.600
improving people's riding.

00:39:24.600 --> 00:39:27.659
And when we were in New York,
we actually had somebody.

00:39:27.659 --> 00:39:29.700
There was this [INAUDIBLE]
called us up and said,

00:39:29.700 --> 00:39:33.580
hey, I've got to be at
this snowboarding mountain

00:39:33.580 --> 00:39:35.820
to kind of do a customer
meeting and ride with them,

00:39:35.820 --> 00:39:37.710
and I don't know
how to snowboard.

00:39:37.710 --> 00:39:41.580
If I buy your board, can I
get up to speed and learn?

00:39:41.580 --> 00:39:44.230
And I was, like,
yeah, I think so.

00:39:44.230 --> 00:39:46.620
And we actually connected him
with one of our pro riders

00:39:46.620 --> 00:39:48.450
in New York to kind
of show him the ropes,

00:39:48.450 --> 00:39:50.370
and I love to close
a deal, but I'm--

00:39:50.370 --> 00:39:53.540
but he was super happy
and actually rode.

00:39:53.540 --> 00:39:56.920
So, yeah, it can definitely
get you into the sport.

00:40:04.180 --> 00:40:06.070
AUDIENCE: So when
you ali, do you

00:40:06.070 --> 00:40:10.270
try to land on the front
wheels because if you

00:40:10.270 --> 00:40:15.340
land on the motors, it
might easily damage it.

00:40:15.340 --> 00:40:19.030
AARON ADERS: Actually, all
the force bypasses the motors.

00:40:19.030 --> 00:40:22.014
So you actually want
to land on your base.

00:40:22.014 --> 00:40:22.930
AUDIENCE: OK, so flat.

00:40:22.930 --> 00:40:24.880
AARON ADERS: Yeah, I mean a more
experienced rider can kind of

00:40:24.880 --> 00:40:27.070
land on an edge or
something like that,

00:40:27.070 --> 00:40:29.310
but landing flat is really
what you want to do,

00:40:29.310 --> 00:40:32.320
and, yeah, you're coming
down on those casters.

00:40:32.320 --> 00:40:34.870
But the way that the
mechanical system,

00:40:34.870 --> 00:40:39.060
you might be able to tell,
if I could pause this,

00:40:39.060 --> 00:40:40.780
it's an animated GIF.

00:40:40.780 --> 00:40:43.860
But the motor is really
just kind of hanging off

00:40:43.860 --> 00:40:45.300
a mount on the front.

00:40:45.300 --> 00:40:48.360
And so all of that load is
going straight through the wheel

00:40:48.360 --> 00:40:50.209
into the deck, and
you know, through you,

00:40:50.209 --> 00:40:51.000
and then back down.

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:52.740
But it kind of
bypasses that motor.

00:40:52.740 --> 00:40:54.656
Really, the motor is
just kind of hanging off.

00:40:54.656 --> 00:40:57.450
And the only load on the motor
is the timing belt. So it's

00:40:57.450 --> 00:41:00.990
built. I mean, we've
done seven stair gaps,

00:41:00.990 --> 00:41:04.240
which is, you know,
maybe, yeah high.

00:41:04.240 --> 00:41:07.320
And, yeah, it's
so funny, you just

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:10.890
have to like channel
that snowboarding

00:41:10.890 --> 00:41:12.360
feeling and those mechanics.

00:41:12.360 --> 00:41:15.520
If you approach like something
new, it's super scary.

00:41:15.520 --> 00:41:17.430
But if you feel like,
oh, this is, you know,

00:41:17.430 --> 00:41:18.390
just imagine the snow.

00:41:18.390 --> 00:41:22.110
Like, channel your five-year-old
self and like see the snow,

00:41:22.110 --> 00:41:23.670
it just magically works.

00:41:23.670 --> 00:41:24.340
It's crazy.

00:41:24.340 --> 00:41:26.400
AUDIENCE: OK, so when
you're dropping down

00:41:26.400 --> 00:41:31.350
from seven stairs, do you land
like power slide or more like a

00:41:31.350 --> 00:41:32.490
skateboard?

00:41:32.490 --> 00:41:33.800
AARON ADERS: You can.

00:41:33.800 --> 00:41:37.145
In fact, one of our riders,
his name is Slide Jump Slide.

00:41:37.145 --> 00:41:40.570
He these slides, jumps,
and lands on a slide.

00:41:40.570 --> 00:41:43.240
But, yeah, it's a super
challenging trick.

00:41:43.240 --> 00:41:45.180
But, yeah, it's definitely.

00:41:45.180 --> 00:41:47.640
I mean, that's like the great
thing about snowboarding,

00:41:47.640 --> 00:41:50.910
and our board is like there's
this endless progression

00:41:50.910 --> 00:41:52.710
and endless styles.

00:41:52.710 --> 00:41:55.980
And so, yeah, you can land
sideways if you really want to.

00:41:55.980 --> 00:41:57.270
AUDIENCE: OK, cool, thanks.

00:42:03.854 --> 00:42:05.020
AARON ADERS: Oh, do we have?

00:42:05.020 --> 00:42:07.632
OK.

00:42:07.632 --> 00:42:10.090
AUDIENCE: You talk a little
bit about the-- your industrial

00:42:10.090 --> 00:42:12.760
design process,
and you talk a lot

00:42:12.760 --> 00:42:17.290
about wanting to mirror the
experience of snowboarding.

00:42:17.290 --> 00:42:18.790
So how did you think
about that when

00:42:18.790 --> 00:42:22.540
you were designing the board and
communicating the visual design

00:42:22.540 --> 00:42:25.780
to a consumer that may not,
you know, have seen the video?

00:42:25.780 --> 00:42:30.820
AARON ADERS: For sure, so for
us, you know, to call this--

00:42:30.820 --> 00:42:31.690
I'm a snowboarder.

00:42:31.690 --> 00:42:33.090
And if this didn't
feel like snowboarding,

00:42:33.090 --> 00:42:34.522
I would have zero
interest in it.

00:42:34.522 --> 00:42:36.730
And so in the beginning,
that's-- it's kind of how we

00:42:36.730 --> 00:42:37.300
got our name.

00:42:37.300 --> 00:42:41.290
So the Turing test of our
board was being able to--

00:42:41.290 --> 00:42:42.880
like falling leaf
down the street.

00:42:42.880 --> 00:42:45.414
So that's the first
move you learn on snow.

00:42:45.414 --> 00:42:47.830
You're just kind of like a
falling leaf down the mountain.

00:42:47.830 --> 00:42:50.080
And so our board had to do that.

00:42:50.080 --> 00:42:54.010
Nothing else can falling
leaf down a city street.

00:42:54.010 --> 00:42:57.550
And so we just kept iterating
and getting into where we

00:42:57.550 --> 00:42:59.200
had enough torque to do that.

00:42:59.200 --> 00:43:02.080
In the beginning, we were--
we were literally burning

00:43:02.080 --> 00:43:03.250
the coils of the motors.

00:43:03.250 --> 00:43:06.640
But it takes a lot of torque,
a powered caster wheel.

00:43:06.640 --> 00:43:10.120
But in terms of the
industrial design,

00:43:10.120 --> 00:43:13.000
honestly, for the
first version, you

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:16.960
can kind of tell the generation
of the person that designed it.

00:43:16.960 --> 00:43:19.391
It kind of looks like
a first NES, or maybe

00:43:19.391 --> 00:43:20.890
the first Playstation,
or something,

00:43:20.890 --> 00:43:25.400
this real edgy, dark,
you know, device.

00:43:25.400 --> 00:43:28.540
But I think that, you know,
when you see it, and--

00:43:28.540 --> 00:43:30.540
and this-- this thing
popping out of the middle.

00:43:30.540 --> 00:43:32.998
I mean, obviously, you're not
going to put your feet there,

00:43:32.998 --> 00:43:35.200
but you know, your feet
are-- you kind of have

00:43:35.200 --> 00:43:37.750
like a notion of-- of kind
of how to stand on it,

00:43:37.750 --> 00:43:40.360
just-- just naturally where
that grip tape is and things.

00:43:40.360 --> 00:43:43.510
But, yeah, I think
with future versions,

00:43:43.510 --> 00:43:46.570
it can be a little bit
maybe more communicated

00:43:46.570 --> 00:43:48.040
like a snowboard.

00:43:48.040 --> 00:43:51.530
Also, you can't really tell
in this photo, but there's--

00:43:51.530 --> 00:43:52.750
it's just bi-directional.

00:43:52.750 --> 00:43:56.390
There's technically
no front to the board.

00:43:56.390 --> 00:44:00.170
We do have some traction
control for beginners.

00:44:00.170 --> 00:44:02.530
So we're sensing which
direction the board's

00:44:02.530 --> 00:44:06.190
going and applying
power relative

00:44:06.190 --> 00:44:07.510
to that, that direction.

00:44:07.510 --> 00:44:09.010
So if you-- you
know, if you switch,

00:44:09.010 --> 00:44:11.440
won't have like
anti-traction control.

00:44:11.440 --> 00:44:13.240
It's got to-- it's got
to follow with you,

00:44:13.240 --> 00:44:14.632
if you go the other way.

00:44:14.632 --> 00:44:16.090
And I think that
kind of helps too,

00:44:16.090 --> 00:44:17.430
because when they
get out the box, so,

00:44:17.430 --> 00:44:18.660
you know, which way is forward?

00:44:18.660 --> 00:44:19.576
But it doesn't matter.

00:44:19.576 --> 00:44:21.580
It just, it knows
which way is forward?

00:44:21.580 --> 00:44:24.790
But I I think there's--
yeah, definitely design wise,

00:44:24.790 --> 00:44:28.240
we can pick up a lot
more in the next version.

00:44:28.240 --> 00:44:30.460
AUDIENCE: And one
other unrelated

00:44:30.460 --> 00:44:34.510
question you mentioned that
you started up in New York

00:44:34.510 --> 00:44:37.000
and this genre of
product immediately

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:38.515
made me think of
Casey Neistat, who

00:44:38.515 --> 00:44:42.040
is a very popular YouTuber
that's always messing around

00:44:42.040 --> 00:44:46.300
with electric, you know,
modes of transportation.

00:44:46.300 --> 00:44:48.274
Has he tried this yet?

00:44:48.274 --> 00:44:49.690
AARON ADERS: You
know, it's funny.

00:44:49.690 --> 00:44:52.690
We-- I don't think
he's tried it.

00:44:52.690 --> 00:44:55.270
We actually ran into him
when we were beta testing.

00:44:55.270 --> 00:44:58.840
It was like 10 degrees
January, New York.

00:44:58.840 --> 00:45:02.580
And there was nobody out
except one of our beta riders.

00:45:02.580 --> 00:45:03.970
It was actually my brother.

00:45:03.970 --> 00:45:06.452
And he was testing along--

00:45:06.452 --> 00:45:07.910
I don't if you've
been to New York,

00:45:07.910 --> 00:45:08.860
but there's like
the Freedom Tower,

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:10.420
and there's this huge bike lane.

00:45:10.420 --> 00:45:11.980
It's really nice and smooth.

00:45:11.980 --> 00:45:13.910
And if it's 10 degrees
out, nobody's on it.

00:45:13.910 --> 00:45:17.865
So he was out there going,
and Casey was actually--

00:45:17.865 --> 00:45:21.470
you know how he rides his
board and films himself,

00:45:21.470 --> 00:45:25.780
and he came up on our beta
rider, and, of course,

00:45:25.780 --> 00:45:27.230
like, he threw this huge slide.

00:45:27.230 --> 00:45:28.360
It was like, whoa!

00:45:28.360 --> 00:45:29.260
What is that?

00:45:29.260 --> 00:45:32.020
And he stopped him,
and he actually put us

00:45:32.020 --> 00:45:35.470
on his daily blog that day.

00:45:35.470 --> 00:45:37.000
And, yeah, our site
was just like--

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:39.041
I mean, it was like 12,000
visitors in the first,

00:45:39.041 --> 00:45:41.980
you know, 20 minutes
after he posted that.

00:45:41.980 --> 00:45:43.480
And all he did was just--

00:45:43.480 --> 00:45:46.570
luckily, my brother had like
one of our promo cards on him

00:45:46.570 --> 00:45:49.924
and just floated that out there,
and we had a ton of traffic.

00:45:49.924 --> 00:45:51.340
And he's a big
snowboarder, and he

00:45:51.340 --> 00:45:52.756
does this like
street snowboarding

00:45:52.756 --> 00:45:54.879
thing where he takes like a--

00:45:54.879 --> 00:45:55.420
I don't know.

00:45:55.420 --> 00:45:57.910
I think it's like a water
ski rope behind a car

00:45:57.910 --> 00:45:59.110
and snowboards around.

00:45:59.110 --> 00:46:02.380
So this is like a lot
better for that than that.

00:46:02.380 --> 00:46:05.080
But, yeah, he's kind
of the perfect person.

00:46:05.080 --> 00:46:07.150
I know that he's really
involved with Boosted.

00:46:07.150 --> 00:46:10.190
So I'm not sure if he has
much interest, but maybe.

00:46:17.060 --> 00:46:19.380
AUDIENCE: So you said something
about traction control,

00:46:19.380 --> 00:46:21.421
and I was wondering if
you could say a few things

00:46:21.421 --> 00:46:24.500
about the hardware that's
inside kind of controlling

00:46:24.500 --> 00:46:25.880
the motors a little bit?

00:46:25.880 --> 00:46:27.290
AARON ADERS: Yeah, totally.

00:46:27.290 --> 00:46:30.440
So the traction control
is remarkably symbol.

00:46:30.440 --> 00:46:33.132
Basically, you know, when
you're going on to turn a car,

00:46:33.132 --> 00:46:35.090
and you start to slide
out, then you, you know,

00:46:35.090 --> 00:46:37.313
slow down those back wheels,
and kind of, you know,

00:46:37.313 --> 00:46:39.480
lessens that slide
out a little bit.

00:46:39.480 --> 00:46:41.880
And so what we do is basically
the same exact thing.

00:46:41.880 --> 00:46:45.530
We're just slowing
down the back wheel.

00:46:45.530 --> 00:46:48.140
But, again, without
being a front end,

00:46:48.140 --> 00:46:50.240
the back can kind of change.

00:46:50.240 --> 00:46:53.750
And so all, basically,
we have just a set

00:46:53.750 --> 00:46:56.450
of positive magnets on one side
instead of negative magnets

00:46:56.450 --> 00:46:59.136
on the other, Hall
sensor, and, you know,

00:46:59.136 --> 00:47:01.510
if it's a positive reading,
we know we're going this way.

00:47:01.510 --> 00:47:03.960
If it's negative reading, we
know we're going that way.

00:47:03.960 --> 00:47:06.410
And then if that
changes, you just

00:47:06.410 --> 00:47:09.050
change the power
going to each motor.

00:47:09.050 --> 00:47:11.690
It happens in milliseconds.

00:47:11.690 --> 00:47:13.280
And it's remarkably simple.

00:47:13.280 --> 00:47:17.890
I just like literally
one Hall sensor,

00:47:17.890 --> 00:47:21.500
and I, actually, there's like
an organization around Hall

00:47:21.500 --> 00:47:23.850
sensors and MEMS and sensors.

00:47:23.850 --> 00:47:26.300
And they found out somehow
we're using that, and I went,

00:47:26.300 --> 00:47:29.510
and I did a presentation at
one of their conferences.

00:47:29.510 --> 00:47:31.190
And they were super
excited until they

00:47:31.190 --> 00:47:33.377
find I only had one Hall
sensor in the board,

00:47:33.377 --> 00:47:35.210
and they were I think
a little disappointed.

00:47:35.210 --> 00:47:38.270
They wanted to buy
more because there

00:47:38.270 --> 00:47:41.270
are people with MRI machines
with thousands of Hall sensors.

00:47:41.270 --> 00:47:45.020
And so, yeah, that was kind
of unexpected and funny.

00:47:58.930 --> 00:48:00.430
AUDIENCE: Hey, I
was just wondering,

00:48:00.430 --> 00:48:04.290
have you guys thought at
all about maybe this product

00:48:04.290 --> 00:48:08.220
in the context of how like
a skate park might evolve?

00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:12.540
And, specifically, I'm thinking
about how skate jumps are very

00:48:12.540 --> 00:48:14.370
different, like,
it's a very different

00:48:14.370 --> 00:48:17.460
than like a proper snowboard
kicker, you know, the landing,

00:48:17.460 --> 00:48:19.590
and how that works, and
is there any thought of,

00:48:19.590 --> 00:48:21.570
like, would this
kind of a product

00:48:21.570 --> 00:48:23.220
work in that kind
of environment,

00:48:23.220 --> 00:48:27.510
not just in like, you know,
hitting stair gaps and rails,

00:48:27.510 --> 00:48:30.370
but also more
snowboard-style jumps?

00:48:30.370 --> 00:48:31.620
AARON ADERS: Yeah, definitely.

00:48:31.620 --> 00:48:34.350
So have you ever
heard of a pump track?

00:48:34.350 --> 00:48:35.500
So it's like these--

00:48:35.500 --> 00:48:37.270
this little track
that's got these bumps.

00:48:37.270 --> 00:48:38.070
And if you're on
a skateboard, you

00:48:38.070 --> 00:48:40.830
can kind of like pump and
keep momentum going around.

00:48:40.830 --> 00:48:43.470
We thought those would
be great, but the scale

00:48:43.470 --> 00:48:44.650
was just far too small.

00:48:44.650 --> 00:48:46.651
It was, you know, built
for a little skateboard.

00:48:46.651 --> 00:48:48.275
And with snowboarding,
you know, you've

00:48:48.275 --> 00:48:50.310
got these massive runs
that are like, you know,

00:48:50.310 --> 00:48:54.360
sometimes 10 lanes wide and,
you know, carving across those,

00:48:54.360 --> 00:48:56.620
I mean, it's just-- you know,
it makes your whole day.

00:48:56.620 --> 00:49:00.390
And so there is definitely
like a larger scale that

00:49:00.390 --> 00:49:05.730
needs to happen with that, and
with the skate park, for me,

00:49:05.730 --> 00:49:08.850
I like more like flat
transition, so maybe more

00:49:08.850 --> 00:49:11.670
like a pyramid rather
than like a quarter pipe.

00:49:11.670 --> 00:49:15.000
I do find that curve,
at least for me,

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:16.590
maybe my skills
aren't good enough.

00:49:16.590 --> 00:49:19.110
But it kind of freaks me out.

00:49:19.110 --> 00:49:21.630
And, you know, I've never really
tried that on a snowboard,

00:49:21.630 --> 00:49:22.680
so I couldn't really tell you.

00:49:22.680 --> 00:49:24.179
But what I do want
to know, and what

00:49:24.179 --> 00:49:27.120
I love doing on this board is
more like, what would be great

00:49:27.120 --> 00:49:29.400
is like a pyramid that
would be like the size

00:49:29.400 --> 00:49:32.134
of this room with huge
walls that, you know,

00:49:32.134 --> 00:49:33.690
kind of transition.

00:49:33.690 --> 00:49:35.020
Those are super fun.

00:49:35.020 --> 00:49:37.590
And I think that
definitely someday there

00:49:37.590 --> 00:49:40.110
will be kind of a
park meant for these,

00:49:40.110 --> 00:49:43.560
but I think it's going to be at
a much larger scale just given

00:49:43.560 --> 00:49:46.150
kind of how snowboarding works
and the fun parts of that.

00:49:50.870 --> 00:49:52.820
Yeah, and on that
note, actually, we--

00:49:52.820 --> 00:49:54.830
you know, Prospect
Park in Brooklyn,

00:49:54.830 --> 00:49:56.579
I don't know if anybody's
ever been there,

00:49:56.579 --> 00:49:58.250
but it's like a LEIF resort.

00:49:58.250 --> 00:49:59.980
It's incredible.

00:49:59.980 --> 00:50:03.140
There is a huge loop
around the park that's

00:50:03.140 --> 00:50:05.570
like four to six lanes
wide that's super fun

00:50:05.570 --> 00:50:07.230
to carve and get up to speed.

00:50:07.230 --> 00:50:09.480
But then there's all these
little paths in the middle.

00:50:09.480 --> 00:50:13.074
And so it's a very
different experience,

00:50:13.074 --> 00:50:14.990
you know, traveling
through these little paths

00:50:14.990 --> 00:50:18.612
and going on the big outer ring.

00:50:18.612 --> 00:50:20.320
But, you know, that's
kind of fun to kind

00:50:20.320 --> 00:50:21.319
of experience with that.

00:50:21.319 --> 00:50:24.930
But when we came to Los
Angeles, and, you know,

00:50:24.930 --> 00:50:28.650
we rode up Griffith Park, which
is one of our favorite runs.

00:50:28.650 --> 00:50:30.530
I mean, that was an even--

00:50:30.530 --> 00:50:32.750
I'd never like used
the same product

00:50:32.750 --> 00:50:34.885
and had such a
different experience,

00:50:34.885 --> 00:50:37.010
you know, being on literally
the side of a mountain

00:50:37.010 --> 00:50:39.590
going up that hill
to Griffith Park.

00:50:39.590 --> 00:50:42.890
And so it's-- it
just blew our minds.

00:50:42.890 --> 00:50:43.790
It was way different.

00:50:43.790 --> 00:50:46.070
And I think there's just
so many different contexts

00:50:46.070 --> 00:50:47.210
you can enjoy this board.

00:50:47.210 --> 00:50:51.969
But I think that bigger,
wider is really nice.

00:50:51.969 --> 00:50:54.260
AUDIENCE: How easy is it to
bring the board on a plane?

00:50:55.475 --> 00:50:56.790
AARON ADERS: Yeah so we--

00:50:56.790 --> 00:50:59.690
we designed the
batteries so that they're

00:50:59.690 --> 00:51:02.510
compliant with TSA regulations.

00:51:02.510 --> 00:51:05.944
And so I usually
carry on the board.

00:51:05.944 --> 00:51:07.610
You always have to
carry on the battery,

00:51:07.610 --> 00:51:09.890
and the remote controls,
there's a battery inside.

00:51:09.890 --> 00:51:11.810
You can check the
board if you like.

00:51:11.810 --> 00:51:13.580
I've actually carried
on two boards.

00:51:13.580 --> 00:51:17.560
They were super annoyed, but
they let me through with it.

00:51:17.560 --> 00:51:19.880
And, yeah, it just
fits in the overhead.

00:51:19.880 --> 00:51:22.760
And a lot of our customers
take them everywhere,

00:51:22.760 --> 00:51:26.300
and that was, you know, a key
feature we really had to have.

00:51:26.300 --> 00:51:28.550
And that's why you see our
battery packs are actually

00:51:28.550 --> 00:51:31.640
two batteries because to stay
under the watt hour limit,

00:51:31.640 --> 00:51:32.900
we had to split the pack.

00:51:32.900 --> 00:51:34.610
And we can get a
lot more mileage

00:51:34.610 --> 00:51:37.880
and stay under that limit.

00:51:37.880 --> 00:51:40.260
Everybody read ride?

00:51:40.260 --> 00:51:42.591
Cool, let's do it.

00:51:42.591 --> 00:51:43.465
[APPLAUSE]

00:51:44.340 --> 00:51:46.490
Appreciate it.

